    <p class="eyebrow">(Running the Workday)</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        This chapter is for the GM. It lays out the shape of a typical workday
        on the severed floor, then offers tables of small events to drop into
        one — for texture, or to seed a deliberate beat. Use as much or as
        little as your story needs.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2>Session vs. Workday</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>One note on terminology first, as the two are easy to confuse.</p>
    <p>
      A <strong>session</strong> is a real-world meeting between you and your players
      — one sitting at the table. A <strong>workday</strong> is one in-game day on
      the severed floor, beginning with the elevator descent and ending with the elevator
      ascent.
    </p>
    <p>
      One session may hold one workday, several workdays, or part of a single
      longer one. You decide how many workdays a session spans, in step with the
      pace of the story.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>The Shape of a Workday</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      A typical workday at Lumon follows a rhythm of arrival, briefing, work,
      break, work, evaluation, and departure. Formalize whichever beats suit
      your campaign — run each in turn, or skip ahead to the moments that
      matter.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Descent</strong> — the elevator door closes upstairs and opens
          downstairs. The innie wakes. A ritual moment, when it serves the story.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Morning Briefing</strong> — the team gathers. The Floor Manager
          (or their proxy) speaks. The day&#x27;s quotas, expectations, or announcements
          are delivered.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Morning Work Block</strong> — the bulk of the day&#x27;s productive
          work.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Mid-Day Break</strong> — the food bar opens. Employees gather, eat,
          and converse. A natural moment for inter-team beats.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Afternoon Work Block</strong> — a continuation of the day&#x27;s
          work, or a new task introduced.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>End-of-Day Evaluation</strong> — quotas are checked. Praise or concern
          is offered. The Floor Manager reviews the day.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Ascent</strong> — the elevator returns. The innie sleeps.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
