    <hr />
    <h2>On Routine, and the Earning of Points</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <strong>Kier Points</strong> are not earned from routine. The day-to-day flow
      of the workday should be played as the rhythm of life on the severed floor —
      not as a series of point-earning opportunities.
    </p>
    <p>
      That said, <strong
        >sustained routine excellence is its own narrative beat</strong
      >. An employee who delivers an impeccable quarter — meeting quota each
      workday, never missing a beat — has earned the recognition of management.
      In such a moment, a Floor Manager may elevate the routine into a story
      beat and award a <strong>Kier Point</strong>, in line with the
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Earning Kier Points</a> rules.
    </p>
    <p>Points are awarded at the GM&#x27;s discretion, in the moment.</p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Stress During the Workday</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      Stress is <strong>GM discretion</strong>. The events on these tables do
      not impose stress automatically. Add (or relieve) stress when the moment
      calls for it — see the <strong>Stress</strong> and
      <strong>Outcomes</strong> sections of
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A long string of interruptions may justify a stress increase. A graceful
      navigation of a Management Visit may justify a reduction. You are the
      judge.
    </p>
