            it chimes again.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>9.</strong> A coworker leaves the room and returns forty minutes
            later, calm, with no account of where they went.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>10.</strong> A coworker greets you by a name that is not yours,
            then corrects themselves too quickly.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>11.</strong> A coworker confides a dream — though dreams should
            not be possible here.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>12.</strong> A coworker stares at the elevator doors for ten minutes.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>13.</strong> A coworker reports another for something small. The
            reported coworker is not seen tomorrow.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>14.</strong> The bathroom is closed &quot;for fumigation.&quot;
            It does not reopen.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>15.</strong> A coworker is led out and returns smiling faintly,
            and is not quite themselves after.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>16.</strong> The wall clock runs six minutes fast. By morning,
            the hallway clock has caught up to it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>17.</strong> The elevator stops on a floor between known floors.
            The doors do not open. Something breathes on the other side.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>18.</strong> A Wellness &quot;gift basket&quot; is given to a
            coworker, who afterward will not speak of it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>19.</strong> A coworker asks for help with something they cannot
            describe, and weeps when you cannot.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>20.</strong> A coworker has gone missing. No one else has noticed.
            Their desk is already reassigned.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2>Table VII — Discoveries</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <em>
        The things we have hidden in the seams of the floor, and the things they
        forgot to hide. Use one when an employee searches, snoops, or asks — or
        leave one where a curious innie is sure to find it.
      </em>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>1.</strong> A handwritten note, signed only with initials.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>2.</strong> A coworker&#x27;s name written on the back of a memo,
            followed by a question mark.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>3.</strong> A photograph of a stranger, expression unreadable.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>4.</strong> A child&#x27;s drawing of a place that resembles the
            severed floor.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>5.</strong> A handwritten page torn from
            <em>The You You Are</em>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong>6.</strong> A keycard that does not belong.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>7.</strong> A grainy security-camera printout showing an unfamiliar
            corridor is left on the printer.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>8.</strong> A scrap of fabric — soft, scented faintly of soap.
            Stained.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>9.</strong> A list of employee codes, half of which are crossed
            out.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>10.</strong> A schedule that does not match the floor&#x27;s published
            one.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>11.</strong> A wrapped piece of hard candy, store-bought. (Impossible
            here.)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>12.</strong> A coworker&#x27;s stress ball, hidden in an unusual
            place.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>13.</strong> A cassette tape labeled with a single word:
            <strong>REMEMBER</strong>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>14.</strong> An incomplete, hand-annotated blueprint of the floor.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>15.</strong> A new entry in your diary, written in someone else&#x27;s
            handwriting.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>16.</strong> A coworker&#x27;s LIEP, its stress checkboxes filled
            to Burnout.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>17.</strong> A small mirror, palm-sized, edges worn.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>18.</strong> A copy of the Compliance Handbook with passages circled
            and underlined.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>19.</strong> A folded note bearing the employee&#x27;s outie&#x27;s
            name — in their own handwriting — that they cannot remember writing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>20.</strong> A door key. No door is known to require it.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
